# Decide Chorus's fate

## Step

The rhizomatic/Chorus claims service runs and injects session briefings,
but its semantic layer is June canary residue (zero preferences, zero
tasks, newest durable claims 06-18) and 13 mutations sit in its outbox.
Settle: is Chorus a canary to quiet down (stop noisy briefing injection,
drain/discard the outbox, park the service) or a real second substrate —
and if real, define Brain ownership, promotion, conflict, and provenance
rules BEFORE letting real claims land, so Brain and Chorus can't disagree
without an owner. Evidence:
[periphery survey](../memory-system-review/periphery-survey.svx)
"Rhizomatic / Chorus claims" + flag #2.

## Decision (Joel, 2026-07-17, grilled live)

**Quiet the canary. Park it.**

1. Stop the session-start briefing injection (live evidence at decision
   time: the grilling session's own briefing carried zero preferences,
   zero tasks, and month-stale June topics — a month of runtime produced
   nothing useful).
2. Drain or discard the 13-mutation outbox — nothing in it becomes a
   live claim.
3. Park the service; no real claims land, so no ownership/promotion/
   provenance rules are owed.

The Brain remains the only substrate. If claim-graph ideas return, they
return as a Brain-owned projection under the
[brain-graph](../brain-graph/brain-graph-brief.svx) effort, not as a
parallel store.
